address: 211 Serangoon Ave 4 #01-10 Singapore 550211 Singapore
comment: Great little cafe to get some coffee and do some reading or work. Wifi is great and outlets are also available, though limited to certain spots. The shop has that Pinterest/hipster/cute aesthetic to it. The staff is also very nice and responsive. A breath of fresh air from The Daily Press, a nearby cafe we went to where they didn't even acknowledge our existence.

address: 211 Serangoon Ave 4 #01-10 Singapore 550211 Singapore
comment: Atmosphere: cute, hipster-ish, bright lighting Service: decent but took awhile to receive my order. But they were nice and said goodbye when we left. Pastries: almond croissant was over-baked making it a little dry. But I appreciated that it wasn't ridiculously sweet like many cafes do now and the amount of almonds too! So that's a plus. Seating can be limited friends that people take a table for studying, laptops, etc. But there's an okay amount of seating. Selection of pastries, pretty good. Everything is supposed to be housemade which is nice as well. People seemed to be ordering the Swiss rolls of different flavors. Earl grey was out but matcha looked yummy. I did not order it but maybe another time if I come check it out. Tip: there's wifi! Tip2: you can order swissrolls in advance for pick up :)

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: Surprised to see all the negative reviews, I definitely enjoyed my bak kut teh and would come again!Peppery clear broth. Pork rib juicy and slight salted,  but mostly peppery and a hint of some kind of other spices. The liver and kidney cooked well!Pork intestine slightly chewy and sweet with a hint of savory to finish.

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: Standards have dropped tremendously. The lukewarm bak kut soup ($7/pax) was the ominous sign of a meal that eventually went downhill. The pork ribs, regardless of which country it came from, was not consistently cooked. It was the first time I encountered so much difficulties tearing off the meat from the bones. When cold lettuces and cold pig liver/kidney slices are thrown into a broth that is not hot enough, the final outcome of the Pig Liver & Kidney Soup ($5) was a mishap that stink of blood. Besides Bak Kut Teh, this place also sells some zi char dishes like the miserable plate of Sambal Potato Leaves ($7) full of withered greens. Other side dishes include braised beancurd skin ($3), braised peanuts ($2) and braised pig skin ($2) but none raised above the bar. Perhaps the Mee Sua Soup ($2) and the Fried Prawn Roll ($10) were the only pillars we could lean on. Ironically, isn't this place known for its Bak Kut Teh in the first place?

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: Heard good things about this bak kut teh but I was throughly disappointed.They claim to serve natural pork, but I found the pork bland and tough. The soup was heavily diluted and tasted like pepper water. The mee sua had too little kidney/ liver and the soup was too reddish due to the blood :( They serve some "zi char" food here. The sambal kang kong needed more flavor. The best dish was probably the dessert, the soybean curd which reminds me a lot of Lao Ban.Overall disappointment :(

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: The soup here is very clear and not too pepperish. The garlic taste is also not over-powering. So if you like your bkt well-balanced, you will like this one.The pork ribs were too dry and tough when we had them, even the "leng-gu". Also didn't quite like the kidney/liver bowl where the soup turned all dark and bloody, and to me undrinkable.The braised pork trotters are good though, tender and succulent. And the braised peanuts flavorful.There was a constant stream of customers on the weekend. the crowd will probably be worse on weekdays when the lunch crowd from the surrounding offices pour in.It's decent and A-OK, so 3-star exactly.

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: Quite disappointed to try the food after reading so much good reviews!We ordered their sliced pork bowl and 1 bowl of their big intestines. Together with the sides dishes - braided peanuts, Mui chai and fried youtiao. Their peppery soup was rather tasteless and tho you can taste the pepper, that's pretty much about it. The sliced pork was a little too fatty for my liking as half the slice will be the fats! The intestines was a little porky in the taste but I guess some folks like that. The side dishes were the decent ones that I have no complains about. All the above with 2 bowls of rice came up to $20 which I thought was a tad expensive as the slices of pork in the bowl was quite little. Safe to say I'm not coming back.

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: An unexpected find! Meant to go shopping at a private sale event but the queue to enter was so long we decided to bail. On the way down we noticed a Baku teh shop (pork ribs in soup) and decided to try it. Later a friend told us it was supposedly a "famous" shop. That would explain the crowd there too. 1. Baku teh - I am biased cos I love this! the soup is soooo good! the sweet black sauce in chili slices (you can mix this yourself) rocks! such a good combination with the pork ribs. 2. Black sauce pork trotter - it was ok but way too much fat! the whole dish was just pork fat (enough to give you a heart attack)! so little meat. not sure if it was meant to be like that but definitely not my taste. 3. Youtiao (fried dough) & steam peanuts - these were served at the beginning of the meal (sorta like mandatory appetizers, you have to pay for these). It was good although the Youtiao was a bit soft & cold.

address: Blk 26, Sin Ming Lane #01-114 Midview City Singapore 573971 Singapore
comment: We came here on a rainy day and decided to order the Bak Kut Teh here.  The Bak Kut Teh soup here is just nice; it is not too peppery and had just the right amount of kick to make you want to drink up everything. The amount of saltiness is just nice and all in all, I personally believe that it is no exaggeration that this is one of the tastiest bak kut teh soup that I have ever drunk. However, I feel that the meat here is not really up to standard; they were a little tougher compared to the best bak kut teh stalls that I have eaten at, and I believe this diminishes the meal somewhat. I always like my meat to be tender and to have the right amount of bite, but the meat here probably doesn't cut it. Still, the whole thing is nice.I also had the pig trotters and the intestines, which were nice but not too fantastic. But overall, if you really want to drink good bak kut teh soup, make this your first stop.

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: The best chicken rice, char siew (BBQ pork), crispy roast pork I've ever had in my life. The souly sauce chicken was smooth and seasoned perfectly - not too salty. BBQ pork and crispy pork are also perfectly done. Definitely a must have next time you're in Singapore.By the way, this place is better than the other restaurant that won the Michelin star -- you know which one I'm talking about.

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: Had this chicken rice at around 1pm was afraid to meet the lunch crowd but thankfully able to grab seats. The chicken is smooth and tender. For a person who hardly eats roast pork, their roast pork is pretty good. Crispy and juicy. I didn't get to eat their dumpling soup as I'm allergic to prawns but my boyfriend got to enjoy them. I can literally count the amount of prawns they put in each dumpling. (I was expecting the minced the prawns instead of putting whole prawns in)Whether I'll come again, definitely yes for a quick simple lunch.

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: It's different. It's rich in flavour. It's old in ways of preparation. You can actually taste how things used to be back then.This chicken rice is class. No frills, just like how they used to make'em in the old days.  Nothing superbly spectacular about it as a whole but you can tell that it's something special.It's a slightly above average plate of chicken rice that gets you there for sure. But there's something about that taste that brings you back to olden days Singapore food. The star however does not lie in the rice or noodles or chilli, the chicken is definitely one of the softest and most moist I've ever eaten!The sauce is uber thick but a tad starchy. It had a slight herbal flavour to it which made it fragrant. This is definitely a very unique alternative to your everyday normal plate of chicken rice. I do for see myself coming back again just for that soft sweet chicken.P.S - Things are a little bit more to the sweet side than salty here I noticed.3.2 STARS

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: Sweet, sweet, chicken rice. The sauce is the magic in this hard to pronounce restaurant. LEE FUN NAM KEE (combination of founder's and his wife's surnames). Now don't forget that because this is where you will experience the sweetest chicken rice sauce ever. The brown sauce that comes with the soya sauce chicken is thick and starchy and so flavourful. You can mix the chicken with the chicken rice and you're set, your meal is complete. If you're not easily satisfied, there are the standard veggies that you can order as a side, the veggies - Kai Lan, comes with sinful pieces of pork lard. YUMMEH. The price of the dishes are higher than your usual chicken rice in the kopitiam but this is a semi-restaurant leh, so the price is not that bad la. The restaurant is always crowded on meal times, both weekdays and weekends. Do make your bookings beforehand.

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: Lee Fun Nam Kee is a reminder that there's more than one way of preparing your chicken rice. I personally like the "normal" Hainanese version, i.e. plain "white" boiled. However, this restaurant, in addition to serving it plain, also offers an awesome soy sauce version. The thick and sweet gravy is poured over the chopped chicken before serving with chicken rice. The rice is slightly oily and very fragrant (which is how chicken rice should be). It's so good that you can just eat it on its own.This restaurant is also highly recommended if you are looking for a nostalgic taste from the 1960s. The restaurant began as a food stall in the old Toa Payoh Lorong 4 food centre in 1966 before moving to its current location.

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: Best steamed chicken rice in Toa Payoh?

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: The Char Sui is savory with very nice crispy skin. The chicken with soy sauce was tender and moist. Loved it! No menu here so I didn't know what else they have but these two dishes were perfect. I will be back for more

rest_name: Lee Fun Nam Kee Chicken Rice & Restaurant
address: 94 Toa Payoh Lorong 4 #01-04 Singapore 310094 Singapore
comment: I am a huge chicken rice fan....lee fun serves really juicy and tender chicken and sesame oil chicken, perfectly executed. The rice is also really fragrant with lotsa chicken flavor. The only problem is the quality of the rice can be variable, and I have had better rice at other chicken rice places. But overall this chicken rice joint is legit and a must try

address: 27 Teck Chye Terrace Singapore 545729 Singapore
comment: Tip: Make a reservation, even on weeknights. We came here for my birthday dinner, and it was a good thing we made reservations as it was packed, even on a weeknight. Even with a reservation, there was no table for 6 of us. As 4 of us got there first, we shared a table with other customers who were finishing up their meals. That must be uncomfortable for the customers. My other friends arrived shortly after the customers left.We ordered quite a lot of food - tom yum seafood soup (white), century egg salad, seafood cake (like fish cake), basil chicken, prawn petai, sambal kangkong, deep fried garlic pork and coconut ice cream dessert. I had the last fresh coconut too. So go early. Everything was delicious and spicy. I was surprised I really liked the century egg salad. The seafood cake was the only thing which could be skipped.The prices were fair and reasonable. It came to the low $20s for each of us. This is a good place for yummy Thai Chinese food, and the seafood too.

address: 27 Teck Chye Terrace Singapore 545729 Singapore
comment: The crab vermicelli is very good. Since we were not able to dine in a large group, I chose to tabao. So ordered quite a good selection of dishes such as Thai fish cake, pandan chicken and sambal Kang Kong. Of course we also must have mango sticky rice. We had Thai ice tea to wash it all down.

address: 27 Teck Chye Terrace Singapore 545729 Singapore
comment: My Oh My.... What A ThaiI've heard of Yaowarat Seafood for a while now, constantly seeing more and more friends liking their facebook page. The gf and I had always wanted to head down but considering it's always just the 2 of us, we felt it wasn't worth it because we can't try much. Happens that it was my parents' anniversary so it gave us the perfect opportunity considering there were 8 of us for dinner! Although it's possible to walk in, seeing how the crowd streams in around 7pm, even on a Wednesday, it's highly recommended that you make a reservation. A glance at the menu show cases the variety of seafood available, from crabs to squid, to sea conch. We decided to go for some classic thai appetizers, and a few seafood dishes to give us a variety of food. Home Made Thai Seafood Cake. These were so so good! It was juicy, sweet, crispy and a real treat. The seafood cakes were beautifully fried and the sweet Chilli it comes with was perfect for the dish. Pity they only had 1 serving left, which was disappointing as we really wanted one or two servings more. A bit strange considering we were the second tables there yet they had already ran out of the seafood cakes. Thai Mango Salad and Thai Papaya Salad. A staple for any Thai restaurant. The salads were very fresh, offering enough punch with its sourness and saltiness. A great appetizer to help build up an appetite! A lot of places tend to hold back the flavors but not here. The flavours were bold and bringing you to Thailand with every bite. Stuffed Chicken Wings  A lot smaller than the picture suggest but still very good. The wings were beautifully fried and the stuffing was tasty. Home Made Prawn Spring Rolls Another great appetizer! The spring roles were thin and crispy, the stuffing, sweet and juicy. The perfect spring role! Crab Bee Hoon Soup. I know I know... Very un-Thai but this is one of our favourite crab dishes and we had to try it and we have noooooooo regrets. The soup was beautifully sweet, not oily and the key to this dish was the very sweet very fresh crab! How often have we eaten crabs that have disappointed but this one absolutely perfect. It was so fresh that I even managed to remove the meat from the claw perfectly. Definitely one of the best crab bee Hoon we've ever had. Steamed Marble Goby, HK style. This was the dish that made everyone's eyes pop. The sauce was not over powering and the fish was very very fresh and perfectly cooked. The meat was still juicy and firm and very flavorful with no trace of any fishiness. Every one of us thought it was very very good and raving about it after dinner. Steamed Seafood Platter. A seafood lovers paradise! With a whole crab, Venus clams and Fresh prawns (and boy were they fresh), all steamed in a sauce, this was definitely the highlight of our dinner. Considering how every protein has a different cook time, this dish was perfect. Gf felt the sauce was a little sweet while I though it was perfect. Overall still a very very good dish. BBQ Lobster with GarlicWith a current offer of a Boston lobster at $5 for every $150 spent, how could we say no! And this isn't some frozen lobster they need to clear either. These are fresh and beautifully cooked lobsters. The garlic compliments it well, not killing the natural sweetness of the lobster. Beautifully cooked.Pineapple fried rice. Definitely recommended! No artificial pineapple taste, rice was fluffy, pineapples added the perfect sour/ sweetness to the dish. Very very  good. Overall, the quality of food here is very very good. We felt that the staff were a little stretched and flustered, forgetting our drinks as it got busier. However, in terms of the quality! Excellent! Freshness is a key and they're certainly not shy to showcase that. We'll definitely be back to try their bamboo clams, crab with vermicelli and their Tom yum soup (I know, how could we not have ordered Tom yum soup right?!). I'd rate the food 4.5*. However, because of some of the starters and desserts not being available, and the slight waiting time to get the staff's attention, I'll need to drop it down to a 4* rating.But, if you're looking for a restaurant that only believes in serving the freshest available seafood, and not overpowering it with sauces than this is definitely the place to visit! All I can say it....... Aroi Mak Mak!

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Have long been meaning to come check out this place! It has 2 of my loves, fish and soup!We ordered their 10 pax set dinner for $288 and it had:Coral trout steamboat - very fresh and sweet meat. Free flow of soup too. I'm really just happy with this fish soup and white rice. Homemade Tofu - very well executed dish. Tofu is soft in the inside and crispy on the outside. Sauce is also delicious!Asparagus with Scallop and Sea Cucumbery in XO Sauce - I love the slight spice that goes with the freshness of the scallop and the vegetable. Golden Roast - this roast chicken is not bad. Claypot Pork Belly with Salted Eggs - this is really a Claypot of goodness! I can't see the salted eggs but every mouthful is damn good!Prawns with sweet spicy Sauce - also not bad. Choice of Mango jelly or turtle shell jelly 龟苓膏  for dessert - nothing very special but a nice end to an awesome meal!Will definitely bring the extended family back to let them have a feast here too!

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Date of visit: 6/16/2022Food tasted ok, but service was so bad that I don't think I will go back. I ordered the value set for 2 for $75.80. This set menu consist of: - the fish soup: MAKE SURE YOU ORDER THE BONELESS ONE, or else you'll end up with only couple of pieces fish meat and the rest only bones! - prawn rolls: pretty good- crab sauce tofu: the crab sauce tasted very good - pudding dessert: I got one herbal jelly and one mango jelly. The herbal jelly is bitter and the mango one is pretty good. You can add sugar syrup on the herbal jelly if you want and add milk on to the mango pudding if you want. I omitted both.In addition to the set menu above, I ordered:- dou miao (S): pretty good- iced barley: on the sweet side- iced water chestnut: on the sweet side MAKE SURE YOU CHECK YOUR BILL BEFORE PAYING. They added one can of coke and 3 wet tissue (40 cents each) that I NEVER ORDERED! BE CAREFUL!

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Zichar dishes were average - 2.5 stars.Fish steamboat - 4.5 starsWith the thick bee hoon, it tasted like really good fish bee hoon soup! I didn't pay though so it might be expensive for what it's worth. The Holland Village XO fish bee hoon might be comparable.Mango pudding - 2 starsToo sweet.Guiling gao - 2.5 starsGood texture but wish it was served with honey. They gave what looked like a sugar syrup.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Fish steamboat is the signature dish here. There are 3 choices of fish:For medium size (recommended for 3 to 4 persons)- Badang - Quite common in many fish soup places $40- Garoupa - This is good and meaty but has some bones when filleted. Bigger chunks that flake $50- Pomfret - Sweet and even texture $60We took the Garoupa. The dish was a good portion and can also be shared with 5 persons. It comes with quite a lot of vegetables inside and some pieces of yam. The soup was really thick and flavourful and the steamboat kept everything piping hot even after the fire had gone out. It's a complete meal with some rice. It was served with their garlic chilli sauce which is quite spicy but really tasty.We ordered some other dishes and really liked the hae cho (prawn rolls). The Indonesian style claypot $13 was quite unctuous but seemed quite fatty as well with lots of skin. Simple stir fried veg was a generous portion for medium $11.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Visited Balestier and Killiney road outlets.For the steamboat, would gave 4 stars for Balestier outlet due to the great tasting soup stock. The 3 stars was given because we felt that there were more fish bone parts than fish meat in the steamboat. The same goes for the Killiney road outlet except the soup stock was not as tasteful as the one in Balestier road.  The way steamboat is serve in this restaurant chain, one does not know what one gets until the dish comes to the table and one starts eating.However, the Killiney road outlet is more spacious than the one in Balestier.I would hesitate to patronise these restaurants on a regular basis.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: This place is an institution.  They could not be bothered if ratings were bad.  Since day one i knew of please wonderful msg laden steamboat it has gotten more prosperous so something must be right.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: The red garoupa hotpot ($35 for 2) itself was quite tasty. Don't get me wrong. But the whole experience just felt underwhelming. By the way, for those not in the know, it isn't actually a "steamboat" you expect in hotpot restaurant where you cook raw food. The dish comes boiling and the ingredients are already cooked when it's presented at the table. I've had this dish at their rival over at Serangoon Road twice before. I remember the soup over there being tastier. But we also ordered other dishes here like hei cho, sambal kang kong and prawn paste chicken wings. All were good but not outstanding. The chicken was particularly tasty. The whole meal for two ended up totaling $80. Felt like a rip off when I saw that we were charged for things like rice (it must be a cultural thing as I've not encountered additional payment for unlimited rice refills in any other country), soup refills (clearly a hidden cost because there's no way anybody would not ask for a refill since the first serving is a pathetic amount based on the shallowness of the pot), chrysanthemum leaves which you add into the soup and paper napkins. The waitress didn't have the initiative to inform that the leaves were an additional cost when she asked if I wanted them (the hotpot already comes with cabbage). Which I guess is typical "service" in Singapore. The "soup refill" and chrysanthemum leaves (a small plate of tatty looking vegetables) was $6.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: My parents are regulars of Whampoa Food Street Keng... they are so regular here that they can even go up to the counter and go "Is Ah Keng (the owner) here? Say Hi for us!" And if he is around, he will come by our table and have a short chat with my parents. If you do come by here, do order their trademark Fish Head Steamboat. I love the soup in the steamboat. Another trademark dish is their hot-plate tofu, prawn-paste chicken, roast chicken, coffee ribs, their cereal prawns and salted egg prawns. Do go down before 6.30pm as that is where the place hits the full house.. so getting a table will be quite difficult after that time.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Located near at the whampoa wet market, this place might be difficult to find for people who don't stay in this vicinity. The shop opens from 5pm onwards till 9 :30 pm and you will realize the food market is relatively empty except for this stall and the drink stall.The food served is fish head steamboat and the cooking method is very authentic, using charcoal to heat the soup. The soup is very rich and you will realize the owner uses a lot of anchovies to cook it. The fish is tender and soft. Do try their duck wings, it is braised in an awesome gravy which does well with it. The meat is cooked to perfection and soft.However the waiting time gets longer if you reach after 6 pm, you can wait for 1 hour, it is that popular.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: This place can get rather crowded and your clothes might stink afterwards. Hence, do not wash your hair before visiting this place or I suggest you may wanna go to the salon after.It is a great venue for family dinner. You may already know that they are famous from the  celebrity-lined wall, however I have not seen any of them in the restaurant. The charcoal-fueled fish steamboat never fail to lift up the family gathering.  They have 3 types of fish to choose from, pomfret, garoupa and batang (boneless). Always choose  the amount of fish +1 more than the number of people you have because portion is rather small or I am a big eater. The soup is souperlicious! I really like the milky salty taste of it. That is the highlight.As for the side dishes, they are all not too bad. You may want to order them, but the highlight is definitely the fish steamboat.  Also, this is definitely a cheaper alternative compared to Imperial Treasure steamboat for their fish feasting.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: Excellent food! Fish broth is so good - I've become a regular. Always full of people - recommend a reservation or go after peak hours

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: I drove down this road almost every weekday for the past two years, but never once looked in. Last week, mum goes, "hey let's eat at this steamboat place in Whampoa", and I'm like, "What? Where?"Yeah, there's a signboard up front, but it really doesn't look like much... until you see the queues. With an S. The night we went the queue stretched from the foot of the stairs (the small, simple lower floor is JUST A DECOY - there's so many more seats UPSTAIRS) to a snakey line along the main road.Before you let that deter you, have patience. When you finally get to it, the steamboat soup makes it all worthwhile. they cook some of the freshest fish I've ever been served, and the flavours are so clean and simple, you'll wonder why new-age/fusion-y restaurants mess with tastes.Oh and before I forget - the steamboat comes to you with charcoal inside, which is as old-timey as you can get! Hipsters will kill themselves to get in.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: i find the fish head soup expensive. we ordered a small 3-4 to share. It was $60. When the soup was served. We counted there were only about 10 pieces of fish. Really? Did they made a mistake by giving us a small 1-2 to share?  Will not be back. Over priced.

address: 556 Balestier Rd Singapore 329872 Singapore
comment: expensive. bad service. the food was below average. they forgot our drinks. when i asked for help the reply was 'what do you want' not how can i help or yes sir...really crap..

address: 470 Lor 6 Toa Payoh Singapore 310470 Singapore
comment: During the Chinese New Year period, we did not have whole version of Dian sum. The food were good , but the service was slow

address: 470 Lor 6 Toa Payoh Singapore 310470 Singapore
comment: Came here for dinner with my grandma and grand aunt. Situated at toa payoh central, the clientele here is mostly families and seniors. Hence, the waiting staff are also slightly on the older side, who are client in dialect and can speak to customers in hokkien and Cantonese. The food here is decent. Not fantastic, but not bad either. Your typical crystal jade standard, if you get what I mean. The char siew and siew yok combination is decent. The char siew was a little too lean though, and probably could have been better if it was slightly more fatty. The stir fried fillet with ginger and scallion was pretty yummy. Love that the fish was fresh :) Sautéed string beans with minced pork is a great fish to go with rice. I love how it has a slightly savory taste which is perfect with rice. A tad oily though! We wanted to order the San bei ji (3 Cup chicken) but unfortunately they removed it from their menu :( we ordered some other stir fried chicken in bean sauce which was way too salty :( not recommended!

address: 146 Potong Pasir Ave 1 #01-135 Singapore 350146 Singapore
comment: I'm surprised Cheryl N. and Raymond L. only gave Shi Mei 3 stars for their chicken rice.  It's not the best, but it's certainly above average.  Shi Mei is my go-to restaurant when I am over in Potong Pasir, and I have been a fan since my first visit in October 2012.  My usual is roasted breast meat, and it's always nice and tender.  My brother swears by the deep fried shrimp rolls, though I am not a fan cos it tastes somewhat greasy and has a weird texture.  Writing this review makes me hungry for their chicken rice!  Goodness!

address: 146 Potong Pasir Ave 1 #01-135 Singapore 350146 Singapore
comment: This little corner eatery in the corner of block 146 serves up decent chicken rice in the day, on top of your favourite zi char, or Chinese a la carte, dishes.I have friends who swear by the chicken rice, but while it's not bad, I've definitely had better. The chicken is a tiny bit tough, and the rice unremarkable. You can also find the common meat dishes along with the chicken rice, including char siew and roasted pork rice.Its zi char dishes are slightly better. You can find the usual fare here, such as hot plate tofu, yam ring, and sambal kang kong. The food won't make you go "wow!", but it's not terrible either. Plus, it's a little on the salty side, so customers with a plainer palate may find it hard to swallow.I suggest heading further down the block for better zi char at the PP881 Eating House, where the food is noticeably better.

address: 146 Potong Pasir Ave 1 #01-135 Singapore 350146 Singapore
comment: This is the best chicken rice in potong pasir as evidenced by the constant crowd of students, office workers and residents. The chicken rice is quite fragrant and fluffy and it won my vote. I try not to eat chicken rice too often because it's unhealthy. I also don't like the garlic aftertaste at most times. But this was fine.There is the chicken cutlet version along with the roast and steamed. Shi mei also does zi char and other dishes but I have never tried it. Chicken rice is still the thing you go for here. Not the best in sg but quite the best in pp unless you add the Sajc chicken rice stall in the equation.

address: Blk 190A Toa Payoh Central #01-522 Singapore 319196 Singapore
comment: If you fancy some cheap Penang food in a no-frills setting, this place is it ! Nestled in a small food court within Toa payoh Central, it is a hidden gem in this food haven. We found it completely by accident and were treated to some good quality penang fare. The char kuay teow was reminiscent of the ones from penang and the chendol was not bad. We will definitely come back to try out the rest !

address: Blk 190A Toa Payoh Central #01-522 Singapore 319196 Singapore
comment: Quite shocking that that the Penang Laksa which consist of thick noodles, onions, sliced cucumber and a few remnants (3 miserable smaller than bite size pieces) of canned sardines would cost $4. While the Assam broth was a good balance of sweet, spicy and sour, I think it is overpriced.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: This place is a work hanger built into a restaurant.  It's a very cool concept. The food is reasonable priced for Singapore. Plates were a good sized.  Chicken was a full breast.  Garlic bread was crispy and good.  I like the ambiance. It's a good place to come and chill. Have. Coffee and small bite or a meal. Fried Cauliflower very good.  Lemoned iced tea very strong. Coffee looks good too. (Didn't try it though. So that's off what I saw being served.) We would come back and eat here.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: I'd have to agree with most reviews / comments from friends, this place has a nice ambience, but food is mediocre. The cafe interior is great, air-conditioned, wide spaces, high ceilings, a range of sofas and seats for the solo people-watcher to diners. Food-wise, nothing to shout about. I would say over-priced too for the type of foods that they serve, but arguably the prices are quite typical of any cafes you'd visit. (The iced espresso ball was $9, and it was really just a little cup of iced latte. Guess you're paying extra for the fun of melting the espresso with milk)It's self-service at this place -- order at the cashier and get a buzzer, pick up your food from the counter once the buzzer rings. They don't charge GST and Service Charge here. They only have 4 parking spaces in front of their outlet (where the signature blue gates are). Free parking available on weekends at the industrial building next to it. Alternatively, limited street parking is also available (60c per half hour, even on Sundays). They are on Burpple Beyond, but there are T&Cs behind the Beyond deals -- a max of 4 redemptions per table, and any Beyond payments need to be made via cash or nets only. For all other payments, credit card is accepted only for bills above $20.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: The craze for this hipster,instaworthy cafe has died down.But the food remains satisfying!My colleagues and I had-All day breakfast - Fish & Chips- Seafood Pasta- Grilled Chicken - Taco Platter The portions were generous, the only downside was that the chicken lacked seasoning. I would definitely order F&C again, feeling blessed as I had 3 awesome F&C from different places this year! (TICM and Workbench!) Wheeler's has a large serving mayo for those who like to splatter their fish with! Fries are plentiful too, it's the kind of fries that are still delish even it's not piping hot. It was a hearty meal overall.The ambience of the place has an industrial chic vibe going on, the signature blue doors, high ceilings are unseaworthy. * Weekday Set Lunch $19.90 for selected mains with soup or salad and a drink.*Water is self serving, I really dislike food establishments that charge for water!

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Have heard much about this place and as this is my first time here, what I heard didn't disappoint. The ambiance and atmosphere was vibrant and the food scrumptious. The soft shell chilli crab spaghetti was a little spicy for me but the Suki beef rice bowl was done just right with the right amount of sauce, and the beef, tender. For drinks, the Hulk, which was a concoction of green Apple, ginger and honey and the Tropical Dream, of mango and raspberry was perfect compliment to the meal.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Wheeler's Yard, you surprise me.Your concept is too cool for school. You are a bike shop, a pop up bar, and an air conditioned cafe all in one. I love how you picked up on today's industrial decor trend and morphed your huge warehouse to house all three concepts.I'm not a bike rider, so I can't comment on your sweet looking bikes, but I am an eater and drinker, so I will give you my 2 cents on that! Your calamari is a great starter; LOVE the sauce it's drenched in though the squid was a bit too chewy at times. Your Caesar salad is my second favourite in Singapore (next to, you guessed it, Salad Stop's haha.) I love how you give me those cute little cookies to go with my coffee, and how I have a good choice of ciders if I'm in the mood for one.And how can I say no to the easily accessible pitchers of ice water, some which are displayed on the back of a bike?I normally decide to cool down in your air conditioned cafe, where I enjoy listening to your awesome pop playlist. I love how I spot neighbours of all ages hanging out here and in the al fresco dining area too. Basically, you know how to appeal to the local community, and you're doing it all right. And hey, you're even willing to serve not-cool-enough people like myself with a smile, so you get all the stars for that!

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Wheeler's Yard is my go-to place during the weekday if I need a place to complete work or do some readings. The high ceilings and spacious arrangement doesn't give a claustrophobic feeling. Best thing is, I don't need to sit elbow to elbow with people and fit for a good cup of coffee. The servers pretty much leave you alone most of the time so don't expect service here. It's something that I don't mind when I prefer to just concentrate on my laptop and my readings. Food wise- the fries are a must-try. My friend and I made a mistake of ordering our mains AND fries. The portion is so huge that even on its own, the two of us could not have finished it. The big breakfast set is rather big also. However, the price did leave a huge hole in my pocket. Overall, good place you want to have some quality time with friends or by yourself.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: What a find!In what feels like the middle of nowhere, Wheeler's Yard doesn't look like much from the street. A big blue door on front of a warehouse doesn't hint at what's behind... but the people standing in front of it madly taking selfies indicates that perhaps something interesting is going on inside.Walk down the side alley and through a big open door and you suddenly realise that this place is choc-full with people drinking coffee and eating brunch. I'm not talking just a dozen people, but a hundred, maybe more! There's two areas to sit. Behind the glass doors, you might be lucky to score a seat on the big communal table where you can read magazines and relax in AC comfort. Outside there's more seating and also the view of the bicycle workshop where you can buy a funky bike or bring yours to be serviced. I spied some cute kids helmets sporting animal faces, and only wished they came in big-kid sizes!We stopped in for drinks only - there's coffee and tea, interesting soft drinks and also a small selection of beers. But many visitors were sharing piles of fries, sweets and brunchy items that looked appetising.It's great to see that the entrepreneurial F&B world is alive and kicking here in Singapore and if Wheeler's Yard is a sign of more fun things to come, then it's safe to say that Singaporeans have a lot to look forward to when it comes to innovative venues.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: I am a strong supporter of bicycles as a mean of transport, and I sometimes miss those Sundays back home when they close some main avenues so we can cycle just for recreation. No wonder any kind of place devoted to cyclists will always catch my attention.Wheeler's Yard is on a quiet area in the border between Whampoa and Toa Payoh. The restaurant is inside a spacious industrial warehouse, sharing the massive space with a bicycle shop and self-labeled atelier. In a time of crammed cafes and confined restaurants dubbed as "intimate", the high ceilings and massive tables of the restaurant are a delight. The whole place is a vintage paradise, highly appealing to architectural restoration enthusiasts. They basically kept as much as they could from the original warehouse and made the restaurant and atelier fit in there, creating a vast place with a warm atmosphere, ideal for groups and sharing.The menu is varied, with some Japanese inspiration and local ingredients. I had a nicely done pan-seared snapper served in a small pool of fragrant mushroom stock. It was not spectacular, but the flavours were wisely balanced. My wife had a sous vide chicken, which was juicy and fairly tasty. We also had the truffle fries, which we liked a lot. They have a small, careful selection of local craft beers at reasonable prices. Another plus is they don't impose service charge, since the place actually works on a self service basis. The food prices are not those of a self-service place, though.All in all, Wheeler's Yard works as a retreat from the race of the chase. It feels ideal for a quiet afternoon in Whampoa (which is quiet enough itself). I can imagine myself arriving there after a long and tiring urban cycle ride. Yeah, that's going on my list.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: I went to Wheeler's Yard yesterday evening with my partner and the first impression was very good. Nestled within an industrial warehouse, it's like a hidden gem that's waiting to be uncovered. The ambience within the cafe is certainly unique - with its high ceiling, warm lighting and consistent bicycle theme. It felt like a place where one could relax and chat with friends for hours. The food and drinks were definitely pricey, especially considering the location and the fact that everything is self-service. We were there too early for dinner, so we ordered a bowl of truffle fries to share ($14.90, i think).The truffle fries were AMAZING. The moment the bowl was set on the table in front of me, I was hit by the aroma of truffles. That was when I knew this was going to be an experience to remember. The fries were hot and crispy and the chef was definitely liberal with the truffle oil and grated cheese. The portion was just right for 2 people, and we polished it off in no time. The truffle aroma stayed with us for the rest of the night, even through dinner. I'm still gushing over it. We'll definitely go back again.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Being a cyclist from the moment I heard of this place I was intrigued. My first thought when I walked in was that it is awesome and very Melbourne...The coffee was good and definitely a stop point after my morning ridesIt definitely had the potential to be a 4 star food experience. Unfortunately we had to send back our burger because the meat was sloppy red raw! So we sent it back and the next one was really good and fresh, which is why I think this place still has potential and  just needs to ask how you want your burger done.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: I was frankly pretty disappointed with the visit. The ambience and layout are really fun and the place looks like it ought to be great. Sadly, the food was only so-so. We went for Sunday brunch and between everyone at the table sampled quite a few items on the menu. I had the Ultimate Beef Yard burger and my wife had the Big Breakfast. My burger was slightly undercooked and VERY greasy and the fries (which I had heard good things about) were dry and overcooked. The breakfast items were rather bland as well. Prices (as mentioned in other reviews) are not cheap and frankly very inflated for the quality. The place is fun to visit and I suspect that's what you pay for. It is family friendly but very, very noisy for lunch on a Sunday - don't expect any intimate conversation. I think this is a low 3 star rating due only to the quirky fun atmosphere but I would not return for the food.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: The drinks/ coffee are good but the food is terrible! I ordered the Salmon Mentaiko pasta which was a chef's recommendation. I love mentaiko everything but this $19.90 pasta was fishy, bland and tasteless all at the same time. It was definitely cooked by someone who could not care less. Even Whampoa Market/ Pastamania serves better food. My partner ordered a fish and chips and beware! It comes with fish bones! You are only paying for the ambience. What a shame.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: A place like this exists in Singapore, holy schnikes! Texas barnyard meets Novena hustle & bustle. At the onset, when you first lay your eyes on this beauty, you begin to wonder, "this place looks out of place doesn't it?" You walk inside this pimped out barnyard and you concur, "this place is really out of place!" But I guess, that is part of the charm of Wheelers Yard, a huge pimped out warehouse located in a quiet street corner of Novena with neighborhood Aunties and Uncles as regular customers.Inside this proverbial barn is a restaurant, bike shop, a pop-up bar/cider stand, and what I swear is a stage concert. Literally, the place can turned into anything the owner desires.  In terms of the food, the Fried Calamari dipped in black sweet sauce is a MUST try. I know I sound like a broken record that this and that is the Best in Singapore. But, why not, I'll say it again, the Best Calamari dish in Singapore. The Calamari portions are huge, even for Singapore and the Sauce was well... the bomb diggitty. The Prawn Aglio Olio, which I seem to try at every restaurant, was good, but doesn't compare to Starker down the road. I didn't try the bbq ribs, but I might as well have had it since my fellow communal seating partner was gorging himself right next to me. Based on his reaction after every bite, it must have been good or at least worth the consideration.  Overall, Wheelers Yard is a MUST SEE cafe and truly embodies the creativity of Singapore and its people.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Whilst the burger was pricey and could have been bigger I can't but rate it as one of Singapore's best offerings.  The Wagyu fat infused patty was close to perfection, rested well and a nice grill to it. The onsen egg precariously resting on top was both theatrical and fun to pop allowing the yolk to coat the ingredients. The pickles were sensibly left on the side as they were sweet and would have distracted from the hero of the dish, the patty.  All this in a great venue. Ask them to keep the fries hit though!

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Great ambience with wide spaces - something hard-pressed to find in Singapore. Food range is surprising wide. Love the food choices we made although the poached egg is still far from world standards. The coffee is good. A glance at the drinks list reveals another surprisingly wide range of whiskeys, cocktails and beers. A bit hidden from the main road but a definite gem if you are looking to chill in a unique and cool environment amidst good beverages and decent food

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: I found a review online that mentioned the Ribeye steak was worth a shot! Steak in a cafe didn't seem like the natural option but none of the other items on the menu impressed me much so I decided to go for it! What's the worst that could happen? $27 wasted and a sad face. Boy! Was I glad I decided to take the path less travelled! The Ribeye steak was delicious (I had it medium done)! Unfortunately, the same cannot be said about their burgers! My friend asked the cashier, "what's good here?"She replied, "up to you lor"Unsatisfied with the answer I chimed in, "but what would you recommend?"She asked, "the burger" He decided to go with her recommendation but we weren't impressed. The meat was subpar. It tasted kinda chewy and over marinated... kinda like cheap sausage meat grounded into a patty? Either she has poor taste or she gave him really bad information. Coffee-wise, I really didn't think that they were as good as Nylon etc. Passable but it wasn't impressive.Service was also rather slow that day. My steak came out on time but my friends' food didn't. Ambiance-wise, Wheeler is unbeatable! A beautiful hipster cafe! I love the concept and the deco. Not so much the location and the parking. There's barely enough lots to fit 5% of the customers. They only have 4 lots out front. All 4 were taken when we arrived. Plus, the remote location (an industrial like area) didn't really help because it wasn't very accessible via public transportation so I wished they had more parking space!

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Food is ok, to medium. I had eggs and bacon breakfast, jus and coffee. You pay for a premium, at a self service station. Where are my 10% service charge going?.. Seriously?I agree the front door is nice.. Inside is a nice concept too. But it doesn't justify the price. For cheaper and better (food) I would go to Jewel cafe instead... It's 15mins away but I'll not feel like raped off on Saturday or Sunday morning for brunch. I tried it once, I'll not go there anymore for sure.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: The hype over the locality of this place, an industrial space functioning both as a bike atelier and a cafe at the same time, Wheeler's Yard is a place where you can get unique bicycles while also having western food items and drinks!The food menu is rather extensive here.And the drinks menu! Rather simple.The Latte ($5) tasted ok with the right amount of milk added. Nothing too great.The Big Breakfast ($14.90) is served with a wholemeal bread toast, scrambled eggs, bacon, sausage, hashbrown & garden salad. This is way better than the coffee although not overwhelming as well. The toast was rather nicely toasted and crusty. The scrambled eggs are nice. The bacon is great. The sausages and the hashbrown are average. The garden salad is also not too bad. In overall, this could have been better.If you live or is around the Balestier area, this place should be considered to have your meal (for its ambience; do not expect too much from the food and drinks)

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: So there's food and coffee here but that's not what I'm talking about (if you must know, its ok).  But the bike shop here is fantastic!  Custom builds from Taiwan.  Amazing little accessories.  Bamboo fenders!  And a smart and enthusiastic staff with a strong love for all things bike.  Ya...I get it...it's about as hipster as you can get but they know how to throw down for reals.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Ok so I ordered a dish called 'sticky ribs' or something like that few weeks ago.I asked for medium rare and later I was told it's already precooked so I just went with it.When it was served oh boy, the worst ribs ever tasted and it was not cheap. It tasted like something out of a can... And why aren't the servers patrolling to see if customers have needs? They just stand behind the counter and chatting away. I was once a part-time waiter back in  UNI, so u must prove ur value. My 2cents: minimum care only gets u minimum wage.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Really nice place.. Great coffee and good brunch items on the menu. Strongly recommended to visit on a weekday as Saturdays and Sundays tend to sometimes get a bit busy.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Amazing space with a good vibe going around. Perfect spot for a read or for a talky talk - the tables are pretty spread apart so you have good noise level. Coffee's good enough but it can be better. Same for the food. If you have that then this place is set.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Looks cool, great concept. Food sucks. Grilled chicken dry and bland. Burger is dry and bland. Truffle fries is decent.

address: 28 Lorong Ampas Singapore 328781 Singapore
comment: Cool bikes, cool owner, very laid back place ... Opening hours is a bit tricky to follow though... Food is, well, I would love it if I can DIY it there! New concept right?

address: 1 Jalan Rajah #01-01 Singapore 329133 Singapore
comment: The burger was so good! I had the Mahalo burger and my husband had the bacon cheeseburger. The fries were really good, too. I loved the pineapple in the Mahalo with the pork patty. Best burger I had! My husband like the bacon cheeseburger. Nothing too special about it though imo. I would definitely go back and try the other speciality burgers.

address: 1 Jalan Rajah #01-01 Singapore 329133 Singapore
comment: I've come to The Burger Bar on a few occasions to satisfy a burger craving when McDonald's just wouldn't do the trick- while satisfying enough to hit the spot, I wouldn't call it the BEST burger you'll likely encounter.The servers at this location always seem miserable to be working and aren't exactly helpful. Not sure of the lack of frustration as it can't be their overwhelming crowds since my each visit has been matched with 0 other patrons. I've always had the BollyWooly- lamb burger with curry remoulade and mango chutney for approximately $12. On the sweetish side given the toppings, but the lamb is juicy and delicious. My biggest hatred for the burger goes to the bun- super soft and gets incredibly soggy if you don't eat immediately. The sweet potato fries are delectable however, so would definitely try those as a side.Burger + side will run you a minimum of $15-17 per person, a bit pricey for what you're getting, but okay enough if the craving calls for it.

address: 1 Jalan Rajah #01-01 Singapore 329133 Singapore
comment: Brought to you by Fatboy's Concept, Burger Bar recently replaced the coffee shop that was at the Day's Hotel, which was always empty.  Judging from my recent visit, the Burger Bar is doing a nice job fulfilling a demand for burgers on Balestier, as the pace was packed at 9pm on a Saturday night. I ordered a bacon cheeseburger and fries to go, and I was not disappointed.  The one weakness has to be the bun again.  Seems like the obsession for a soft bun in Singapore, while great for cold sandwiches and on its own, is quite difficult for a juicy burger. The liquid totally overwhelms the buns and the bun crumbles.  But let's also talk about what Burger bar does right.  The patty was solid and so were the fries.  The price point is very good - $8-10 for a burger, $3.50 ad more for fries.  Definitely a place that you can come to weekly without breaking the bank, for a decent burger and fries.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Three words... All day brunch.  How can anyone say no to that?  I mean the Genius!! And they also offer organic options, free flow Procecco, I mean how can you say NO!  That is the genius of this restaurant.  All of the best offerings are here, no need to go anywhere else.  Best of the best dishes? Of course the organic Eggs Benny.  fish and chops are also to fire for. crunchy inside and not soggy or to great.  chips are nice and firm with a bit of a softness on the inside, the best are the beef meatballs.  yes, I who does not eat meat on the regular for dietary reasons, cannot get enough of these.  These meaty morales are flavorful and succulent ...OH I could eat some now just thinking about it!!I digress,  they do have an awesome full Italian menu but honestly, u cannot get past the all day brunch.  Service is speculation ask for vijay he will give you the best wine recommendation.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Lunch set at $19.90++Be warned, the set lunch portions are SMALL! It started with a cioppino (3 stars). The seafood didn't taste very fresh and the soup/stew itself was unremarkable. The main, a spaghetti aglio olio (3 stars) with tiger prawns, was cooked al dente. Major plus points. But again the prawns didn't taste fresh and had the sort of crunchy flavorless texture that makes me dislike prawns. Lastly, you get coffee/tea OR tiramisu. We had the tiramisu (3 stars). The small slice didn't wow - I thought my aunt's tiramisu tasted better.The pizza we had came with artichokes, black olives, Parma ham (4 stars). This was far better! Thin crust, but not very generous with the ingredients.Don't think I'll be in a hurry to come back.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Evian water is very pricey and they just served without you ordering for it.  Food wise is ok although portion is small even for a small eater.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Absolutely meh service & bland food I've experienced in awhile. I'm not sure who the owner is but he/she should have no business pretending to be in the food business - the only good thing I can say about this place is that there are other real restaurants here that serve real good food with real good service.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: This a nice tucked away treat.. Not far from anything.. However not main street.The food is almost as awesome as the service, which is exceptional. The staff are great, such a refreshing change to have competent and knowledgeable staff. This is important as they steer you in the right direction.The food is amazing, there probably isn't a bad dish.. Probably.. All that I have had are amazing.The starters are great. And the mains are so very generous and tasty. The Italian theme doesn't overpower the food, and they cater for all tastes.Having been with children too.. I can assure they cater for them too.Great for couples, groups and families. Have the Seafood in a Bag.. Just perfect.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Love this place! Delicious food, LOVELY service, and a nice atmosphere. This is my go to place for weekend lunches, but it's honestly good for any occasion.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: This is one of the best Italian restaurant in Singapore, in my opinion. The quality of the cooking is in the league of Valentino's although they do not have as much traditional cooked items (and I am not complaining as long as what is on the menu is done well). In terms of ambience, I am glad they have shifted to Greenwood Avenue from Jln Pemimpin. The restaurant offers modern, chic, casual dining and is much larger with both indoor and outdoor seating vs its previous location. Its staff strength has also swelled to cater to the larger seating capacity.  Marcus and his team always makes me feel welcome whenever I drop by. If you drive (and parking is a bitch here), there's a valet service. I love the squid ink pasta and squid ink risotto which you don't need to pre-order, unlike Valentino's. You can taste the freshness and tenderness of the seafood, plus the pasta and risotto are done al dente (and I am pretty fussy that this basic stuff ought to be done right) as it should.  They are prepared using authentic squid ink sauce and not squid ink pasta.  The pizza is good too (thin crust) with just the right amount of balance between cheese and ingredients and their seafood is one of the freshest you can get. I was told the seafood is hand-picked at the fish market every morning.  I have no complaints about the steak, nicely grilled on the outside and juicy and tender (not chewy) on the inside, cooked as well as can be expected. In summary, the quality and consistency of the food here is amazing considering the copious amount of food being prepared for its ravenous crowd.And the chocolate verdant dessert is to die for, crispy on the outside and soft molten chocolate lava flowing from the inside.  We tend to over-eat and often end up with no room for dessert. When we are here, we make sure we exercise restrain so that we don't miss out on the dessert. The wine menu has also been much improved and now comes with a much larger variety of Italian wine.  It's a great place to dine with a large group of friends or with the family. And having said that, I should organize a group dinner here soon. I am glad to see that it is crowded and the restaurant is doing well so that more people in Singapore will continue to enjoy quality Italian fare.Bon appetit!!

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Based off lunch.Went there for lunch one day with my sister because we were tired of Lucky Place Coffee Shop and Pepperoni's. Will never go back again. I think the only okay was the coffee. Oysters had sand, the rest of the food was difficult to finish... service was poor. They don't bother waiting for you to finish your food before bringing out the next course... (and why the rush? There were, what, 3 occupied tables?)Horrid experience, although the ambiance was nice, being quiet and well done up. Bright side was that the food was so bad we could focus on conversation.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Great service with the staff giving us a delicious dessert platter upon finding out that one of our party were celebrating his birthday, food that shines with the deliciousness of the produce and surprisingly reasonable prices. There's basically nothing much more you can ask for. The drinks list is quite comprehensive as well.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Really liked this place. Great food and service. Price accordingly to quality of the food. Definitely worth a come back. Burrata was excellent.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Modern-chic space with ample seating options, indoors and outdoors. Wait staff attentive and knowledgeable (of the menu). Menu with quite a wide variety of modern Italian fare. Food was delicious - we went for dinner and had the Scallop Pasta as well as the Burrata and Parma Ham Pizza. Both were delicious.

address: 12 Greenwood Ave Singapore 289204 Singapore
comment: Very delicious food and portion side was perfect......portions tend to be small in Singapore restaurants.  Tasted fresh and service was the best I have experienced in Singapore.  I had Linguine Vongole, clams were well cooked with a light white wine broth.  My husband had seafood pasta in a bag.  It was really cooked in a bag.  The tomatoe sauce was light and did not over power the seafood.  The owner was very kind and welcoming.  My husband and I had a very pleasant conversation with her.  It was very nice of her to take time from her busy restaurant.  She was very attentive to all customers and her wait staff was well trained in providing great service.  Well worth the price.

address: 1378 Ang Mo Kio Ave 1 Bishan 569981 Singapore
comment: this will be my first and last review of a McDonald's outlet.i grew up on these stuff.so i know first hand how kids will always love them!well, some adults too?!they enjoyed a meteoric rise in SG since their record breaking debut at liat towers in 1979!apparently, that outlet set a record for the world's highest number of burgers served, back then.fond memories of  their cute ridout garden outlet, ideal for a cheap date, that also screened world cup football.but since coming to terms that any kind of fast food is not the best of diet, despite constant reassurance otherwise from none other than donald thompson himself, i must admit i'm no longer an addict.now my only indulgence is when i'm overseas and there is absolutely nothing else worth eating!ok, this outlet deserves special mention mainly because it is located in beautiful bishan park.be it sunrise or sunset, you can just chill to take in the view.the siamese McCafe twin here, serves surprisingly good coffee.piped music, well ventilated outdoors, pleasantly air conditioned indoors and en suite toilets, in an environment that is always kept spick and span.a friendly mix of youthful and elderly staff here, make you feel right at home with their fast and efficient service.but it is what shows, in the eyes of the children, at the very mention of a visit here that is priceless.

address: 158 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 4 Singapore 560158 Singapore
comment: Weekends are meant for good meals and with the sibling's recommendation, we have agreed to head down to Ang Mo Kio Hong Kong Street Zhen Ji for a Cze Char dinner despite the heavy downpour.The dish was a noteworthy item just as recommended on their menu. Cuttlefish given was generous and was soft and chewable while the Sambal was not too spicy together with the cut pieces of Fried Kang Kong.Large chunks of fish meat with slices of ginger and vegetables together with thick bee hoon are the usual sights that we expect from Cze Char's stall Fish Meat Noodle Soup. I was rather disappointed with the soup as it was rather bland without much taste but on a good note, usage of MSG is minimal.The exterior texture of the roll was indeed very thin and crispy, unlike what I had in most Cze Char Stall. As for its fillings, its rather ordinary, pairing up with the sweet sauce provided.The pork ribs are indeed very flavourful with sweetness and sour taste. It was intense and the amount of meat given was generous. It's recommended just as what they state on their menu."Wok Hei" taste from the "San Lao" Hor Fun was present. This individual serving of Hor Fun had a significant use of fish slices as well as bean sprouts.It was a tasty and recommended dish on its menu but, to be honest, it's good but not to die for as there are better ones out there.Though the cereal prawn was packed with fragrance and hints of milk powder, we still find that the taste of prawns was kind of lacking and bland. The taste from the "star" of the dish was not up to our expectation but instead the cereal that is complimenting the prawns taste better as a whole. Well, I would have skipped this dish.With some hits and misses, if I'm going for popular dishes like San Lao Hor Fun, Fish Meat Noodle Soup and Crispy Prawn Roll, I will most likely go to the usual Holland Village XO Fish Head Bee Hun. However, their menu was rather standard and not with a variety like Hong Kong Street. In addition, with so many dishes ordered, we felt that the price was reasonable & pocket friendly for a popular Cze Char place like this. It is definitely a good place for a family meal during the weekends and do note that reservations can be made in advance for big groups only.

address: 158 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 4 Singapore 560158 Singapore
comment: This used to be the small Hong Kong Street Chun Kee at Block 151, but when the owner sold the shop and moved to block 158, they did not know that the new owner would register the new shop under the same name. Hence you know have two zi char shops both famed for their sliced fish hor fun under the same name, Hong Kong Street Chun Kee both within walking distance of each other!Nonetheless, my family decided to give the original zi char shop a try.1. Hong Kong Fried Noodles $4.50The noodles were reasonably wet, even with some wok hei! The portions are generally huge and you can easily share this plate of noodles. One of the best hong kong fried noodles I have eaten in a long while!2. Yang Chow Fried Rice $4The Wok hei here was alot stronger than the hong kong fried noodles, but my dad felt like he tasted some MSG. But my mother and I didn't feel thirsty after the meal. There were a couple of crunchy fresh prawns and the rice was very flavourful.3. Sweet and Sour Pork (Small) $10For $10, they are very generous, there was alot to eat. The pork was very tasty and tender, however the pork could be abit more crispy. Nonetheless, a great place for a great family meal, with a very small bill.Do make a reservation if plan to eat here from 7pm onwards, they get very busy and sometimes the kitchen falls behind on the orders, which is expected for these cofffee shop zi char stalls.

address: 158 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 4 Singapore 560158 Singapore
comment: Tried the seafood fried rice, clay pot mee and sambal sweet potato leaves.Seafood fried rice taste nice and big portion at $4.50Clay pot mee taste yucky n starchy with very few ingredients yet for the price of $8sambal sweet potato leaves at $9 --- nothing special and not worth.No crowd when visit at 8.45pm on a Thursday night.

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: I didn't do this establishment justice by merely posting a few hurried photos(without comments) of their chicken on the rack and by simply checking in. This place has always been a family favourite for years (since the 80's) and it's never failed us yet. The "auntie" who makes the chicken and the rice and the amazing soup is still there governing the place. Her chicken rice is fragrant, fluffy and cooked with just the right amount of gasp... chicken fat and 1 bowl of rice is never quite sufficient. The other thing that I come here for, is, the free flow of soup. Yes the soup might be a little too salty, & yes... its also, maybe a little too peppery... BUT it is unbelievably addictive. I have seen people do takeaways with their own carriers (mind you, they are large carriers) for the soup. and oh yes, of course, the chicken is tender, juicy and faultless to say the least.Hands down... this is the best chicken rice in Singapore, in my opinion. Its just too bad that I don't live in the north anymore. And this place isn't quite as accessible. But hey... Singapore's really tiny so what's an extra 15mins on the road.

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: This is a place where parking is limited and is in a "so close yet so far" location to my home. I have only bought the chicken rice to go. Besides chicken rice, it also serves tze char dishes like other types of chicken, fish (including fish head curry), various types of vegetables, seafood, meat, etc. The roast chicken is silky tender and the rice is so fragrant I can smell it despite it being in its packet and plastic bag. The whole car is redolent of it that you just want to devour the packet of chicken rice immediately. You are warned. Luckily it dissipates quicker than durian smell. Like what Cheryl N reviewed, the rice is good enough to eat on its own without any dark soy sauce or even chili sauce. I just found out they also do delivery which may be more convenient than driving over to da pao the food.

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: I'll give it a 3* because the prawn roll was not up to scratch. It was more porky than prawny, and also very floury. The fish head curry while was delicious but the fish head was so disintegrated like it was already eaten into :( very bad presentation. The clay pot tofu was decent. Good amounts of roast pork and the yam was soft and fluffy. So in conclusion : go for the chicken and fish head curry. But ask them to watch that the fish is whole and not over cooked.

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: Never forget how the owner shamed poor people and normal working folks (taxi drivers). Even if it is good food we should never condone and allow such to prosper. straitstimes.com/singapo…

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: The most memorable chicken rice that i've tasted was dabao-ed (takeaway) by S. It was the most fragrant and fluffy rice cooked in chicken fat that i've tasted. I immediately proclaimed it to be the best chicken rice in Singapore in between gobbles. According to S, it was a random buy but i thought we hit chicken rice jackpot. It was only when i took a closer look at the stall that i realize this is no ordinary chicken rice stall. They have won some award back in 2009 for their traditional Hainanese dishes.I like the broken and slightly soft rice grains. This shows that they have been simmered in a rich stock of fried ginger, garlic, chicken stock (and some fats) and salted for additional flavor. Some people have complained that this is too healthy. Seriously?? I don't care as long as it tastes good. The fragrance of stock has penetrated and locked itself within each grain of rice and you can simply eat this on its own. No need for chili or dark soy sauce (i thought the dark soy overpowers the flavor of the rice). I actually contemplated having a second bowl of rice! Amazeballs!The chicken is nicely flavored as well. They served us breast meat for the individual plates though. I should have said i want the thigh meat for that additional succulence and tenderness. The breast meat wasn't dry though and was juicy enough.The chili was a killer. It really stings. There is a nice sourness and spiciness to the blend of ginger, garlic and chili. Go easy on it if you can't take chili.

address: 8 Braddell Rd Singapore 359898 Singapore
comment: Wow. Best Hainan chicken I've had in Singapore! Better than the famous hawker center ones. Get the Chinese Spinach with Superior Stock. Has goji berries and other tasty herbs, perfect match for the chicken.

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: Surely representing the best hainanese chicken joint in Singapore as you can see line started at pre-opening.  Chicken is porched and then soaked in cold bath to conceal and retain its juiciness in the chicken which makes the meat silky and moist. Rice is fragrant with a touch of coconut which it's super tasty Absolutely must try

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: Came by for a light lunch the other day and it was a sweaty experience! The queue for this Michelin Bib Gourmand stall was ~10-15 minutes at 12:30 pm on a Sunday, except it was 85F outside or 97F after factoring humidity. Luckily Singaporeans queue and there was also a covered waiting area.Prices have gone up drastically due to the chicken shortage from Malaysia.Ordered the chicken thigh rice for $8, cash only. The rice was extremely fragrant, and the chicken was world class juicy. The sauce on top was just world class! The chili dipping sauce was quite spicy too!There are additional tables behind the stalls, except there are no fans!

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: 100% behind the hype on this place. It was on Anthony Bourdains "No Reservation" and has a Michelin star & it's star dish - chicken rice ... comes in at a whopping total of $6 (Singapore dollars ... so even cheaper for USA). 3 different sizes depending on your hunger level, and I opted for the medium... however, I wish I got the large because it was just that good!The rice was ok, nothing spectacular, the sauce on top is what makes the flavor pop there but the chicken.. just wow. It is SO SO SO juicy and tender. I am literally googling how to cook any kind of chicken dinner in my future just like that. I dare say the best chicken I've had. Go, you won't be disappointed!

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: SO DELICIOUS SO CHEAP. CASH ONLY! All the hype is right! You'll find this stall in the third(?) row in the food markets. We had read that you would have to wait 40-60 minutes during lunch time. Maybe we got lucky on our vacation, but we only waited 5 minutes on line, and got our food quickly. Obviously get the chicken rice (medium) - there's a star on the menu for most popular plate. The rice is super fragrant and delicious, more moist than I expected. Chicken is delicious as well - you may not even need any sauces. Must come here!! And definitely try other stalls here as well - there's a nice juice and smoothie stall right next to here :)

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: This place deserves a 6-star rating. Where have you been all my life!? I ate it once and had to keep going back. I woke up dreaming of it for breakfast, wished it was lunch, and possibly fast forward to dinner for this Hainanese Chicken Rice. I love the unpretentious hawker vibe, and then this amazing National dish, a dish a song should be written about -- chicken is super smooth, tender, flavorful. The rice is not over powering but also fragrant and tasty. And it's nice this is a locally loved joint, not just coz of the media hype. Live long and prosper!

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: I wonder why this chicken rice stall is so famous? Because Anthony Bourdain featured it? Dishes are expensive comparing to the ambiance. No ac, humid, noisy, too much foot traffic... don't waste your time here. The quality of the chicken is not there. I've eaten at less known stalls and they taste way much better. Aragon & rude wait staff. And you have to take your own dishes as it's a self service place. Pay so much and serve yourself. No meaning... The chicken meat sucks. More bones than meat! Give this place a miss... you won't miss it...

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: If you want flavorful and fragrant chicken rice, tender and delicious chicken, and overall a super delicious rice plate for an incredible price....this is it. My friend and I were crazy to think that we'd only share one medium plate. We ended up ordering seconds. The rice with the chicken and the sauce (amazing) over the entire dish was literally *chef's kiss* I don't know how else to explain it. And it's super affordable. You can't get a dish like this for ~$3.50 USD back in the States....Don't be scared by the line because it goes by pretty quickly. We went around the time they opened to avoid the line (which we did!!), but since we ordered seconds, we had to wait in line that time- but it did not take long! Definitely avoid lunch hour to be safe because the hawker stalls get CROWDED and you might not be able to score a seat!

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: What else hasn't been said about the super popular Tian Tian chicken and rice stall? I'm not sure if I can add anything else. Yes, Bourdain was here. As usual, he is right. This quintessential Singaporean dish of chicken and rice is so perfectly done that you can't find fault in it. Incredibly soft chicken, fragrant rice and the sauce is deliciously spiced with ginger puree. I ordered a large portion (S$8.80 for a large though?!) so I could get more chicken and got the soy egg for extra protein. There wasn't a wait when I came in at 11am. The crowds came at lunch time when the surrounding office workers were out. I'm not one to stand in line for a long time and there are other chicken and rice stalls at Maxwell's which are probably worth a try too.

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
comment: Tian Tian does not make the same Hainanese chicken rice dish that your mom used to make (sorry Mom, it's true)!  Actually, I cannot really say that my mom ever cooked this dish... but if she had, then it still would not have compared.  Tian Tian's chicken rice dish truly lives up to the legend it has become!There are enough reviews detailing the deliciousness and tenderness of this dish, so I will provide you with a pro tip - the line here can get long quickly, so plan to stop in at an off-time (ya know, not during the typical lunch/dinner rush times).  I stopped in early on a Friday afternoon and walked right up and ordered - score!  Shortly after I sat down to wait the brief wait for my order, the line grew ten-plus long in a snap.Tian Tian is definitely a must-try in Singapore!*****FIVE STARS*****

address: 1 Kadayanallur St #01 -10/11 Maxwell Food Center Singapore 069120 Singapore
